<p>
  The sunk cost fallacy is when you keep choosing something because of
  what you already spent, even when the next move no longer makes sense.
  Time, money, and effort that are already gone cannot be rescued by
  losing more time, money, and effort.
</p>
<p>
  The better question is simple:
  <strong>If I were starting fresh today, would I still choose this?</strong>
  If the answer is no, quitting is not failure. It is making room for a
  better bet.
</p>
<hr class="post-divider" />
<p>
  <strong>&#127916; Example:</strong> you buy a movie ticket, sit down, and
  realize after twenty minutes that the movie is terrible. Staying for two
  more hours will not make the ticket cheaper. Leaving gives you the
  evening back.
</p>
